in_class_description_detail: NA

A transition category made up of grasslands which have been modified by artificial fertilisers, slurry, intensive grazing, herbicides or drainage, and consequently have a range of species which is less diverse and natural than unimproved grasslands.
Grasslands dominanted by Juncus rushes
Tussock grasslands dominanted by Molinea.
Obviously planted woodland of any age
Vegetation dominated by trees more than 5m high when mature, forming a distinct, although sometimes open, canopy.
Vegetation dominated by trees more than 5m high when mature, forming a distinct, although sometimes open, canopy.  broadleaved woodland: 10% or less conifer in the canopy
Vegetation dominated by trees more than 5m high when mature, forming a distinct, although sometimes open, canopy.  coniferous woodland: 10% or less broadleaved in the canopy.
Seral or climax vegetation dominated by locally native shrubs, usually less than 5 m tall, occasionally with a few scattered trees.  Dominated by Gorse (Ulex species).

Grassland in this category is often unenclosed, as on hill-grazing land, and occurs on a range of acid soils (pH less than 5.5). It is generally species-poor, and often grades into wet or dry dwarf shrub heath, although it must always have less than 25% dwarf shrub cover
efg_name: Derived semi-natural pastures and old fields
efg_description: T7.5 Derived semi-natural pastures and old fields

in_class_description_detail: Typically enclosed and usually more intensively managed than acid or calcareous grassland (except on roadside verges), this category encompasses a wide range of communities occurring on neutral soils (pH 5.5-7.0).
Often unenclosed grasslands, not managed intensively, and occur on calcareous soils (pH above 7.0).

Meadows and pastures which have been so affected by heavy grazing, drainage, or the application of herbicides, inorganic fertilisers, slurry or high doses or manure that they have lost many of the species which one could expect to find in an unimproved sward. They have only a very limited range of grasses and a few common forbs

A diffuse category covering certain Molinia grasslands, grasslands with a high proportion of Juncus species, Carex species or Filipendula ulmaria, and wet meadows and pastures supporting communities of species such as Caltha palustris or Valeriana species, where broadleaved herbs rather than grasses, predominate
Areas dominated by Pteridium aquilinum, or with scattered patches of this species.
Vegetation with greater than 25% cover of ericoids or small gorse species in relatively dry situations forms this category.
Primarily woody vegetation with more than 25% cover of ericoids and/or small Ulex species.
Blanket bog comprises Sphagnum-rich vegetation on deep peat, forming a blanket over both concave and convex surfaces, on level to moderately sloping ground in the uplands.
efg_name: Boreal, temperate and montane peat bogs
efg_description: TF1.6 Boreal, temperate and montane peat bogs

in_class_description_detail: Raised bogs are found on estuarine flats, river flood plains and other level areas with impeded drainage in the lowlands, also at moderate altitudes, where they may grade into blanket mire.
efg_name: Boreal, temperate and montane peat bogs
efg_description: TF1.6 Boreal, temperate and montane peat bogs

in_class_description_detail: Wet modified bog vegetation with little or no Sphagnum, often with bare peat. Dry modified bog is dominated by Calluna vulgaris and other ericoids, or by Eriophorum vaginatum, on peat more than 0.5m deep.
efg_name: Boreal, temperate and montane peat bogs
efg_description: TF1.6 Boreal, temperate and montane peat bogs

in_class_description_detail: Fens are defined as minerotrophic mires, usually over peat more than 0.5 m deep (but see E3.3). The water table is at or just below the surface.
Patches of bare peat more than 0.25 ha in extent (that is, approximately 50 m x 50 m).
efg_name: Boreal, temperate and montane peat bogs
efg_description: TF1.6 Boreal, temperate and montane peat bogs

in_class_description_detail: Swamp contains tall emergent vegetation typical of the transition between open water and exposed land. Swamps are generally in standing water for a large part of the year, but may occasionally be found on substrates that are seldom immersed, as in the later stages of the seral succession to marshy grassland.
Defined as water lying beyond the limits of swamp or emergent vegetation, although it may contain submerged, free-floating or floating-leaved vegetation.
Zostera, green algal beds or brown algal beds
Includes mud and sand flats
Vegetation peculiar to this area, characterised by species such as Frankenia laevis or Suaeda fruticosa,
Comprises the three early successional stages of dune formation, less stable and with low vegetation cover
All grassland occurring on consolidated and flattened dunes
All heathland occurring on consolidated and flattened dunes
All scrub occurring on consolidated and flattened dunes
Cliffs formed of rock (including chalk) with less than 10% vascular plant cover.

Includes both natural and artificial exposed rock surfaces where these are almost entirely lacking in vegetation, as well as various forms of excavations and waste tips. Significant communities of mosses, lichens and ferns growing on walls or rock ledges

Arable cropland, horticultural land (for example nurseries, vegetable plots, flower beds), freshly-ploughed land and recently reseeded grassland, such as rye grass and rye- clover leys, often managed for silage.
Lacking vegetation but human-made
Lacking vegetation and natural

A transition category made up of grasslands/forbs which have been modified by artificial fertilisers, slurry, intensive grazing, herbicides or drainage, and consequently have a range of species which is less diverse and natural than unimproved grasslands.
